{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491013"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:27:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:27:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"804"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/804"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.06,0.26,0,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"804"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54974"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/804"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"804"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40492"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"536"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"924"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1050"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42150"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54974"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman is brought into the Emergency Department after a motor vehicle crash. She is able to recall the events and was driving across an intersection when her vehicle was hit on the driver\u0027s side by a car running the red light. The car door was pushed in and she now has severe pain in the right side of her chest and this makes breathing difficult. On examination her blood pressure is 124/86 mmHg and pulse 108/min. As the examination proceeds the patient struggles with her breathing, which becomes increasingly shallow. The breath sounds are reduced on the right and that side of the chest recedes on inspiration.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cardiac tamponade","Simple pneumothorax","Tension pneumothorax","Splenic haemorrhage","Flail chest"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe term \u0027\u003Cstrong\u003Eflail\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Echest\u003C/strong\u003E\u0027 has different meanings and implications for the clinician and the radiologist. A flail segment is the result of fractures of at least two adjacent ribs, with breakages in at least two places, creating a \u0027floating\u0027 segment. A force producing an injury of this type will almost certainly have also led to underlying lung contusion. Apart from the lung damage, this type of injury will lead to a compromise of respiratory effort through paradoxical movement of the chest wall. In other words, when the patient attempts to take a breath in, the broken segment of chest wall, will cave inwards, compromising the respiratory effort. This is a life-threatening situation, often needing mechanical ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWorryingly, radiologists frequently use the flail chest expression to describe adjacent rib fractures, where there may be not clinical evidence of potential respiratory impairment. To the clinician, the term \u0027flail chest\u0027 should alway make them alert to the possibilities of imminent acute respiratory failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECardiac tamponade is unlikely given the blood pressure is maintained; likewise for splenic haemorrhage although it can be maintained for a period before rupture. Furthermore, these two options do not explain the paradoxical respirations. Either a simple or a tension pneumothorax is definitely possible as a consequence of the injury and rib fractures, however neither option explains the chest wall moving in on respiration, i.e. flail segment. In a tension pneumothorax any indrawing of the chest wall would be very unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Paradoxical respirations should alert the clinicians to respiratory emergencies such as flail chest."],"references":["Dogrul BN, Kiliccalan I, Asci ES, et al. Blunt trauma related chest wall and pulmonary injuries: An overview. Chin J Traumatol 2020; 23:125-38"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40492"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"804"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40492"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-12T08:50:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-12T08:51:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"804"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54974"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{